.TH "TEMPORAL" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal \- Temporal
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Temporal\f[B]\f[R] object enables date and time
management in various scenarios, including built\-in time zone and
calendar representation, wall\-clock time conversions, arithmetics,
formatting, and more.
It is designed as a full replacement for the \f[CR]Date\f[R] object.
.SH DESCRIPTION
Unlike most global objects, \f[CR]Temporal\f[R] is not a constructor.
You cannot use it with the \f[CR]new\f[R] operator or invoke the
\f[CR]Temporal\f[R] object as a function.
All properties and methods of \f[CR]Temporal\f[R] are static (just like
the \f[CR]Math\f[R] object).
.PP
\f[CR]Temporal\f[R] has an intricate and powerful API.
It exposes over 200 utility methods via several classes, so it could
appear very complex.
We will provide a high\-level overview of how these APIs are related to
each other.
.SS Background and concepts
JavaScript has had the \f[CR]Date\f[R] object for handling date and time
since its first days.
However, the \f[CR]Date\f[R] API is based on the poorly designed
\f[CR]java.util.Date\f[R] class from Java, which was replaced in the
early 2010s; but, because of JavaScript\(cqs goal of backward
compatibility, \f[CR]Date\f[R] sticks around in the language.
.PP
The important lesson to preface the whole introduction is that \f[B]date
handling is complex\f[R].
Most of the problems of \f[CR]Date\f[R] are fixable by adding more
methods, but a fundamental design flaw remains: it exposes so many
methods on the same object that developers are often confused about what
to use, leading to unexpected pitfalls.
A well\-designed API not only needs to do more, but also should do
\f[I]less\f[R] with each level of abstraction, because preventing misuse
is as important as enabling use cases.
.PP
\f[CR]Date\f[R] objects wear two hats simultaneously:
.IP \(bu 2
As a timestamp: the number of milliseconds or nanoseconds elapsed since
a fixed point in time (known as the \f[I]epoch\f[R]).
.IP \(bu 2
As a combination of components: year, month, day, hour, minute, second,
millisecond, and nanosecond.
The year, month, and day identifiers only make sense with reference to a
\f[I]calendar system\f[R].
The whole combination maps to a unique instant in history when
associated with a time zone.
\f[CR]Date\f[R] objects provide methods for reading and modifying these
components.
.PP
Time zones underlie a significant number of date\-related bugs.
When interacting with a \f[CR]Date\f[R] via the \(lqcombination of
components\(rq model, the time can only be in two time zones: UTC and
local (device), and there\(cqs no way to specify an arbitrary time zone.
Also lacking is the concept of \(lqno time zone\(rq: this is known as a
\f[I]calendar date\f[R] (for dates) or \f[I]wall\-clock time\f[R] (for
times), which is a time you \(lqread off a calendar or clock\(rq.
For example, if you are setting a daily wake up alarm, you will want to
set it to \(lq8:00AM\(rq regardless of whether it is daylight saving
time or not, whether you have traveled to a different time zone, etc.
.PP
A second feature lacking from \f[CR]Date\f[R] is a calendar system.
Most people may be familiar with the Gregorian calendar, where there are
two eras, BC and AD; there are 12 months; each month has a different
number of days; there\(cqs a leap year every 4 years; and so on.
However, some of these concepts may not apply when you are working with
another calendar system, such as the Hebrew calendar, the Chinese
calendar, the Japanese calendar, etc.
With \f[CR]Date\f[R], you can only work with the Gregorian calendar
model.
.PP
There are many other undesirable legacies about \f[CR]Date\f[R], such as
all setters being mutating (which often causes unwanted side effects),
the date time string format being impossible to parse in a consistent
way, etc.
In the end, the best solution is to build a new API from scratch, which
is what \f[CR]Temporal\f[R] is.
.SS API overview
\f[CR]Temporal\f[R] is a namespace, like \f[CR]Intl\f[R].
It contains several classes and namespaces, each of which is designed to
handle a specific aspect of date and time management.
The classes can be grouped as such:
.IP \(bu 2
Representing a time duration (a difference between two time points):
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
Representing a time point:
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
Representing a unique instant in history:
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
As a timestamp: \f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
As a date\-time component combination paired with a time zone:
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R]
.RE
.IP \(bu 2
Representing a time\-zone\-unaware date/time (which are all prefixed
with \(lqPlain\(rq):
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
Date (year, month, day) + time (hour, minute, second, millisecond,
microsecond, nanosecond): \f[CR]Temporal.PlainDateTime\f[R] (Note:
\f[CR]ZonedDateTime\f[R] is equivalent to \f[CR]PlainDateTime\f[R] plus
a time zone)
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
Date (year, month, day): \f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate\f[R]
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
Year, month: \f[CR]Temporal.PlainYearMonth\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
Month, day: \f[CR]Temporal.PlainMonthDay\f[R]
.RE
.IP \(bu 2
Time (hour, minute, second, millisecond, microsecond, nanosecond):
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime\f[R]
.RE
.RE
.RE
.PP
Furthermore, there\(cqs also another utility namespace,
\f[CR]Temporal.Now\f[R], which provides methods for getting the current
time in various formats.
.SS Shared class interface
There are many classes in the \f[CR]Temporal\f[R] namespace, but they
share many similar methods.
The following table lists all methods of each class (except conversion
methods):
