.PP
With these tables, you should have a basic idea of how to navigate the
\f[CR]Temporal\f[R] API.
.SS Calendars
A calendar is a way to organize days, typically into periods of weeks,
months, years, and eras.
Most of the world uses the Gregorian calendar, but there are many other
calendars in use, especially in religious and cultural contexts.
By default, all calendar\-aware \f[CR]Temporal\f[R] objects use the ISO
8601 calendar system, which is based on the Gregorian calendar and
defines additional week\-numbering rules.
\f[CR]Intl.supportedValuesOf()\f[R] lists most of the calendars likely
to be supported by browsers.
Here we provide a brief overview of how calendar systems are formed to
help you internalize what factors may vary between calendars.
.PP
There are three prominent periodic events on Earth: its rotation around
the sun (365.242 days for one revolution), the moon\(cqs rotation around
the Earth (29.53 days from new moon to new moon), and its rotation
around its axis (24 hours from sunrise to sunrise).
Every culture has the same measure of a \(lqday\(rq, which is 24 hours.
Occasional changes such as daylight saving time are not part of the
calendar, but are part of the time zone\(cqs information.
.IP \(bu 2
Some calendars primarily define one year as 365.242 days on average, by
defining years to have 365 days, and adding an extra day, the \f[I]leap
day\f[R], about every 4 years.
Then, the year may be further divided into parts called months.
These calendars are called \f[I]solar calendars\f[R].
The Gregorian calendar and the Solar Hijri calendar are solar calendars.
.IP \(bu 2
Some calendars primarily define one month as 29.5 days on average, by
defining months to alternate between 29 and 30 days.
Then, 12 months may be grouped into a year of 354 days.
These calendars are called \f[I]lunar calendars\f[R].
The Islamic calendar is a lunar calendar.
Because a lunar year is artificial and does not correlate with the
season cycle, lunar calendars are generally rarer.
.IP \(bu 2
Some calendars also primarily define months based on lunar cycles, like
lunar calendars.
Then, to compensate for the 11\-day discrepancy with the solar year, an
extra month, the \f[I]leap month\f[R], is added about every 3 years.
These calendars are called \f[I]lunisolar calendars\f[R].
The Hebrew calendar and the Chinese calendar are lunisolar calendars.
.PP
In \f[CR]Temporal\f[R], every date under one calendar system is uniquely
identified by three components: \f[CR]year\f[R], \f[CR]month\f[R], and
\f[CR]day\f[R].
While \f[CR]year\f[R] is typically a positive integer, it may also be
zero or negative, and increases monotonically with time.
The year \f[CR]1\f[R] (or \f[CR]0\f[R], if it exists) is known as the
calendar epoch, and is arbitrary for each calendar.
\f[CR]month\f[R] is a positive integer that increments by 1 every time,
starting at \f[CR]1\f[R] and ending at \f[CR]date.monthsInYear\f[R],
then resetting back to \f[CR]1\f[R] as the year advances.
\f[CR]day\f[R] is also a positive integer, but it may not start at 1 or
increment by 1 every time, because political changes may cause days to
be skipped or repeated.
But in general, \f[CR]day\f[R] monotonically increases and resets as the
month advances.
.PP
In addition to \f[CR]year\f[R], a year can also be uniquely identified
by the combination of \f[CR]era\f[R] and \f[CR]eraYear\f[R], for
calendars that use eras.
For example, the Gregorian calendar uses the era \(lqCE\(rq (Common Era)
and \(lqBCE\(rq (Before Common Era), and the year \f[CR]\-1\f[R] is the
same as \f[CR]{ era: \(dqbce\(dq, eraYear: 2 }\f[R] (note that year
\f[CR]0\f[R] always exists for all calendars; for the Gregorian
calendar, it corresponds to 1 BCE due to \c
.UR https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomical_year_numbering
astronomical year numbering
.UE \c
).
\f[CR]era\f[R] is a lowercase string, and \f[CR]eraYear\f[R] is an
arbitrary integer that may be zero or negative, or even decrease with
time (usually for the oldest era).
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Always use \f[CR]era\f[R] and \f[CR]eraYear\f[R] as a
pair; don\(cqt use one property without also using the other.
In addition, to avoid conflicts, don\(cqt combine \f[CR]year\f[R] and
\f[CR]era\f[R]/\f[CR]eraYear\f[R] when designating a year.
Pick one year representation and use it consistently.
.PP
Be careful of the following incorrect assumptions about years:
.IP \(bu 2
Don\(cqt assume that \f[CR]era\f[R] and \f[CR]eraYear\f[R] are always
present; they may be \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
Don\(cqt assume that \f[CR]era\f[R] is a user\-friendly string; use
\f[CR]toLocaleString()\f[R] to format your date instead.
.IP \(bu 2
Don\(cqt assume that two \f[CR]year\f[R] values from different calendars
are comparable; use the \f[CR]compare()\f[R] static method instead.
.IP \(bu 2
Don\(cqt assume that years have 365/366 days and 12 months; use
\f[CR]daysInYear\f[R] and \f[CR]monthsInYear\f[R] instead.
.IP \(bu 2
Don\(cqt assume that leap years (\f[CR]inLeapYear\f[R] is
\f[CR]true\f[R]) have one extra day; they may have an extra month.
.RE
.PP
In addition to \f[CR]month\f[R], a month in a year can also be uniquely
identified by the \f[CR]monthCode\f[R].
\f[CR]monthCode\f[R] usually maps to the month\(cqs name, but
\f[CR]month\f[R] does not.
For example, in the case of lunisolar calendars, two months with the
same \f[CR]monthCode\f[R], where one belongs to a leap year and the
other one does not, will have different \f[CR]month\f[R] values if they
come after the leap month, due to the insertion of an extra month.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] To avoid conflicts, don\(cqt combine \f[CR]month\f[R]
and \f[CR]monthCode\f[R] when designating a month.
Pick one month representation and use it consistently.
\f[CR]month\f[R] is more useful if you need the order of months in a
year (e.g., when looping through the months), while \f[CR]monthCode\f[R]
is more useful if you need the name of the month (e.g., when storing
birthdays).
.PP
Be careful of the following incorrect assumptions about months:
.IP \(bu 2
Don\(cqt assume that \f[CR]monthCode\f[R] and \f[CR]month\f[R] always
correspond.
.IP \(bu 2
Don\(cqt assume the number of days in a month; use
\f[CR]daysInMonth\f[R] instead.
.IP \(bu 2
Don\(cqt assume that \f[CR]monthCode\f[R] is a user\-friendly string;
use \f[CR]toLocaleString()\f[R] to format your date instead.
.IP \(bu 2
Generally, don\(cqt cache the name of months in an array or object.
Even though \f[CR]monthCode\f[R] usually maps to the month\(cqs name
within one calendar, we recommend always computing the month\(cqs name
using, for example,
\f[CR]date.toLocaleString(\(dqen\-US\(dq, { calendar: date.calendarId, month: \(dqlong\(dq })\f[R].
.RE
.PP
In addition to \f[CR]day\f[R] (which is a month\-based index), a day in
a year can also be uniquely identified by the \f[CR]dayOfYear\f[R].
\f[CR]dayOfYear\f[R] is a positive integer that increments by 1 every
time, starting at \f[CR]1\f[R] and ending at \f[CR]date.daysInYear\f[R].
.PP
The concept of a \(lqweek\(rq is not connected with any astronomical
event, but is a cultural construct.
While the most common length is \f[CR]7\f[R] days, weeks can also have
4, 5, 6, 8, or more days \(em or even lack a fixed number of days
altogether.
To get the specific number of days of the week of a date, use the
date\(cqs \f[CR]daysInWeek\f[R].
\f[CR]Temporal\f[R] identifies weeks by the combination of
\f[CR]weekOfYear\f[R] and \f[CR]yearOfWeek\f[R].
\f[CR]weekOfYear\f[R] is a positive integer that increments by 1 every
time, starting at \f[CR]1\f[R], then resetting back to \f[CR]1\f[R] as
the year advances.
\f[CR]yearOfWeek\f[R] is generally the same as \f[CR]year\f[R], but may
be different at the start or end of each year, because one week may
cross two years, and \f[CR]yearOfWeek\f[R] picks one of the two years
based on the calendar\(cqs rules.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Always use \f[CR]weekOfYear\f[R] and
\f[CR]yearOfWeek\f[R] as a pair; don\(cqt use \f[CR]weekOfYear\f[R] and
\f[CR]year\f[R].
.PP
Be careful of the following incorrect assumptions about weeks:
.IP \(bu 2
Don\(cqt assume that \f[CR]weekOfYear\f[R] and \f[CR]yearOfWeek\f[R] are
always present; they may be \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
Don\(cqt assume that weeks are always 7 days long; use
\f[CR]daysInWeek\f[R] instead.
.IP \(bu 2
Note that the current \f[CR]Temporal\f[R] API does not support
year\-week dates, so you can\(cqt construct dates using these properties
or serialize dates to year\-week representations.
They are only informational properties.
.RE
.SS RFC 9557 format
All \f[CR]Temporal\f[R] classes can be serialized and deserialized using
the format specified in \c
.UR https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc9557
RFC 9557
.UE \c
, which is based on \c
.UR https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc3339
ISO 8601 / RFC 3339
.UE \c
\&.
The format, in its full form, is as follows (spaces are only for
readability and should not be present in the actual string):
.IP
.EX
YYYY\-MM\-DD T HH:mm:ss.sssssssss Z/±HH:mm [time_zone_id] [u\-ca=calendar_id]
.EE
.PP
Different classes have different requirements for the presence of each
component, so you will find a section titled \(lqRFC 9557 format\(rq in
each class\(cqs documentation, which specifies the format recognized by
that class.
.PP
This is very similar to the date time string format used by
\f[CR]Date\f[R], which is also based on ISO 8601.
The main addition is the ability to specify micro\- and nanosecond
components, and the ability to specify the time zone and calendar
system.
.SS Representable dates
All \f[CR]Temporal\f[R] objects that represent a specific calendar date
impose a similar limit on the range of representable dates, which is
±10\(ha8 days (inclusive) from the Unix epoch, or the range of instants
from \f[CR]\-271821\-04\-20T00:00:00\f[R] to
\f[CR]+275760\-09\-13T00:00:00\f[R].
This is the same range as valid dates.
More specifically:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R] and \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] apply
this limit directly on its \f[CR]epochNanoseconds\f[R] value.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDateTime\f[R] interprets the date\-time in the UTC
time zone and requires it to be ±(10\(ha8 + 1) days (exclusive) from the
Unix epoch, so its valid range is \f[CR]\-271821\-04\-19T00:00:00\f[R]
to \f[CR]+275760\-09\-14T00:00:00\f[R], exclusive.
This allows any \f[CR]ZonedDateTime\f[R] to be converted to a
\f[CR]PlainDateTime\f[R] regardless of its offset.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate\f[R] applies the same check as
\f[CR]PlainDateTime\f[R] to the noon (\f[CR]12:00:00\f[R]) of that date,
so its valid range is \f[CR]\-271821\-04\-19\f[R] to
\f[CR]+275760\-09\-13\f[R].
This allows any \f[CR]PlainDateTime\f[R] to be converted to a
\f[CR]PlainDate\f[R] regardless of its time, and vice versa.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainYearMonth\f[R] has the valid range of
\f[CR]\-271821\-04\f[R] to \f[CR]+275760\-09\f[R].
This allows any \f[CR]PlainDate\f[R] to be converted to a
\f[CR]PlainYearMonth\f[R] regardless of its date (except if a non\-ISO
month\(cqs first day falls in the ISO month \f[CR]\-271821\-03\f[R]).
.PP
The \f[CR]Temporal\f[R] objects will refuse to construct an instance
representing a date/time beyond this limit.
This includes:
.IP \(bu 2
Using the constructor or \f[CR]from()\f[R] static method.
.IP \(bu 2
Using the \f[CR]with()\f[R] method to update calendar fields.
.IP \(bu 2
Using \f[CR]add()\f[R], \f[CR]subtract()\f[R], \f[CR]round()\f[R], or
any other method to derive new instances.
.SH STATIC PROPERTIES
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration\f[R]
Represents a difference between two time points, which can be used in
date/time arithmetic.
It is fundamentally represented as a combination of years, months,
weeks, days, hours, minutes, seconds, milliseconds, microseconds, and
nanoseconds values.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Instant\f[R]
Represents a unique point in time, with nanosecond precision.
It is fundamentally represented as the number of nanoseconds since the
Unix epoch (midnight at the beginning of January 1, 1970, UTC), without
any time zone or calendar system.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Now\f[R]
Provides methods for getting the current time in various formats.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.PlainDate\f[R]
Represents a calendar date (a date without a time or time zone); for
example, an event on a calendar which happens during the whole day no
matter which time zone it\(cqs happening in.
It is fundamentally represented as an ISO 8601 calendar date, with year,
month, and day fields, and an associated calendar system.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.PlainDateTime\f[R]
Represents a date (calendar date) and time (wall\-clock time) without a
time zone.
It is fundamentally represented as a combination of a date (with an
associated calendar system) and a time.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.PlainMonthDay\f[R]
Represents the month and day of a calendar date, without a year or time
zone; for example, an event on a calendar that recurs every year and
happens during the whole day.
It is fundamentally represented as an ISO 8601 calendar date, with year,
month, and day fields, and an associated calendar system.
The year is used to disambiguate the month\-day in non\-ISO calendar
systems.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.PlainTime\f[R]
Represents a time without a date or time zone; for example, a recurring
event that happens at the same time every day.
It is fundamentally represented as a combination of hour, minute,
second, millisecond, microsecond, and nanosecond values.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.PlainYearMonth\f[R]
Represents the year and month of a calendar date, without a day or time
zone; for example, an event on a calendar that happens during the whole
month.
It is fundamentally represented as an ISO 8601 calendar date, with year,
month, and day fields, and an associated calendar system.
The day is used to disambiguate the year\-month in non\-ISO calendar
systems.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R]
Represents a date and time with a time zone.
It is fundamentally represented as a combination of an instant, a time
zone, and a calendar system.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal[Symbol.toStringTag]\f[R]
The initial value of the \f[CR][Symbol.toStringTag]\f[R] property is the
string \f[CR]\(dqTemporal\(dq\f[R].
This property is used in \f[CR]Object.prototype.toString()\f[R].
